[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] A presidential election was held in New Jersey on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1789 United States presidential election.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] The state legislature chose six representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] New Jersey, which had become the 3rd state on December 18, 1787, unanimously cast its 6 electoral votes for George Washington during its first presidential election.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] New Jersey was also the only state in the Union at the time where land-owning women were allowed to vote without the Nineteenth Amendment being in place.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Elections to the Massachusetts Senate were held in 1788 to elect 40 State Senators.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Candidates were elected at the county level, with some counties electing multiple Senators.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] For election, a candidate needed the support of a majority of those voting.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] If a seat remained vacant because no candidate received such a majority, the Massachusetts General Court was empowered to fill it by a majority vote of its members.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Exact totals for Smith, the incumbent Senator, are unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] William Williams, Ebenezer Pierce, John Bacon, and William Walker also received votes, though exact totals are unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Dwight was subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Thomas Durfee, Walter Spooner, and Elisha May also received votes, but their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Exact totals for the Anti-Federalist ticket were not listed.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Unaffiliated candidates Peter Coffin and John Choate also received votes, but their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Jonathan Greenleaf was subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Incumbent Senator David Smead was not re-elected, and his exact vote total is unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Bliss and Sexton were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Waterman Thomas, Daniel Cony, and Henry Dearborn also received votes, but their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Since no candidate received a majority of votes cast, the General Court elected **Dummer Sewall** to the seat.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Exact totals for Anti-Federalist ticket are not listed.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Nathaniel Gorham, William Hunt, John Brooks (Federalist), William Hull, Joseph Curtis, James Winthrop and Elbridge Gerry also received votes, though their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Isaac Winslow, Hugh Orr, Joseph Bryant, James Briggs, and Ebenezer White also received votes.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Nathaniel Low also received votes, but his exact total is unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Edward Cutts and Nathaniel Wells were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788 United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina** were held on November 24 and 25, 1788 to select five Representatives for two-year terms from the state of South Carolina.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The elections resulted in two candidates in support of Washington's administration and three candidates opposed to his policies.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Smith defeated two candidates in the first election of the 1st congressional district, known as the Charleston District.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke defeated Robert Barnwell in the first election of the 2nd congressional district, known as the Beaufort-Orangeburg District.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Daniel Huger won the first election of the 3rd congressional district, known as the Georgetown-Cheraw District.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Sumter won the first election of the 4th congressional district, known as the Camden District.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Tudor Tucker won the first election of the 5th congressional district, known as the Ninety-Six District.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-connecticut] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
